		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">This research programme would investigate the optimum design and economic viability of the Vortex Screw Concentrator Wind Turbine (CWT).  The performance of a CWT with its smaller central turbine and outer static concentrator blades is similar to that of a conventional turbine of the same diameter as the outer concentrator blades.  The economic advantages of the CWT come as the scale of the system increases.  Then the additional cost of constructing the static concentrator blades is outweighed by the savings made in building small central rotating turbine.  Preliminary economic analysis suggests that net savings start to be made at machine diameters around 10m  and considerable savings appear likely for 30m machines.  The technical design of the CWT will build on the work already done by David Olivieri at the Open University and the aerodynamic expertise of the Aerospace Group at Manchester University.  Wind tunnel scale models of a complete system would be built and tested in the department's new Environmental Wind Tunnel.  When these CWT performance results have been obtained it will then be possible to assess the economic viability of the CWT system compared to conventional wind turbines.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
